# NOTE: Keep this list short (~8 entries). Remove old ones as new ones land.
CHANGELOG = [
    "Stat-elixir pad + pre-memorized utility spells for F<N> plants (build 397). The b396 inventory grants closed the consumables gap but the stat profile + spellbook were still underbaked: F15 humans/dwarves had no permanent stat elixirs (despite real F15 survivors typically finding 2-3), and elves at F10+ had memorized only the Mind Touch cantrip from the starter pack. Two coordinated changes in playtest_harness.py:_plant_survivor_baseline. (1) Permanent stat-elixir pad: +1 to each of STR / DEX / INT per 5 floors of depth (F5 -> +1, F10 -> +2, F15 -> +3, F20 -> +4, F25 -> +5). Stacked equally across stats because elixirs are race-agnostic drops. Pushes F20+ humans into casting range (default INT 10 + 3 race-bias + 4 elixir = 17), keeps F15- humans non-casting (matches the human-as-late-bloomer archetype), and gives all races meaningful late-game scaling beyond level-based unspent_stat_points. F15 elf jumps from INT 16 to INT 19 (slot capacity 9 -> 11), F15 dwarf STR 16 -> 19 (more raw combat). (2) Pre-memorized utility spells via new _grant_memorized_spells helper: tier list scaling with depth -- F5+ Minor Heal (Lv0), F8+ Heal (Lv1), F10+ Ice Shard (Lv0), F12+ Stone Skin (Lv2 defense), F15+ Lightning Bolt (Lv2 damage), F18+ Greater Heal (Lv2), F22+ Mass Heal (Lv3). Each spell is added only if the planted character has slot capacity (get_max_memorized_spell_slots) for it, so dwarves and low-INT humans skip cleanly. Verified profile: F15 elf carries Minor Heal + Heal + Ice Shard + Stone Skin + Lightning Bolt + cantrips (8/11 slots used); F20 human / elf both carry 6 memorized spells (10/14 and 10/17 slots used); F25 elf has the full caster build (Mass Heal at 13/24 slots). Combined with b396's stat-derived HP/MP recompute, F15 elf goes from 148/110 HP/MP to 154/119, F20 elf from 198/166 to 206/178. The buff is calibrated to mirror what a real F<N> survivor would have accumulated, not to make plants invincible.",
    "Survivor inventory grants for F<N> plants + vendor identify oscillation fix + non-game_loop wedge escape (build 396). Three coordinated changes. (1) `_grant_survivor_inventory` in playtest_harness.py: scales an items pack with start_floor to mirror what a real F<N> player would have looted / bought across the F1..F<N-1> stretch. F1+ always gets Cooking Kit (addresses the 12/90 starvation deaths in the b394 F15-plant sweep -- Cooking Kit was pulled from starter pack in b358 to make F3 cooking a real decision, but a F15 survivor would have one by now). F5+: 3 Healing Potions, 2 Scroll of Identify, +3 Lantern Fuel cans. F8+: Curing Kit, 2 Greater Healing Pots, Mapping scroll, 3 Mana Potions, +2 Fuel. F12+: 2 Superior Healing Pots, 2 Scroll of Protection, 2 pre-crafted Bratwurst sausages. F15+: 2 Master Healing Pots, Scroll of Restoration, Scroll of Teleportation, +2 Fuel. F20+: +2 Master Healing Pots, +2 Mapping, +2 Protection. F15-plant agent now carries ~1060 HP of healing budget on top of full 154 max HP, comparable to a player who survived to F15 organically. (2) Vendor-shop identify policy oscillation fix in smart_policy: prior gate `obs.last_action != proposed` only blocked the SAME slot from immediate repeat, so with 2+ unidentified items the loop oscillated id4 <-> id5 indefinitely (b395 seed=223 dwarf F13 burned 900+ turns alternating two scroll identify attempts). Tightened to `last_action.startswith('id')` -- any prior id<N> means we've already tried identifying THIS vendor visit and should leave. (3) Non-game_loop wedge escape: the b395 wedge break only fired in movement modes (game_loop, stairs_up_mode, stairs_down_mode); the vendor_shop identify wedge slipped through. Extended the wedge break to ALL modes -- when freeze_streak >= 30 in a non-movement mode, force 'x' (back) to drop the agent into game_loop where the wayfinder can re-evaluate. 'x' is the standard cancel/leave key across most modes; if a mode doesn't accept it the dispatch falls through harmlessly. Mini-sweep verification (30 seeds x 3 races x 1500T F15-plant): pre-b395 9/90 wedged; b395 wedge-only fix had 2/90 unresolved freezes; b396 has 0/90 wedge-break fires, 0/90 max_osc >= 100, 0/90 max_freeze >= 50. Mean moves 391/run, mean deepest F16.7, max F22.",
    "Smart-policy wedge break for freeze + persistent oscillation loops (build 395). The b394 F15-plant sweep surfaced a long-tail smart-policy bug: 9/90 runs wedged 500-2200 turns burning the whole 2500T budget on period-1 'l' (lantern) loops or period-2 'wn'/'ew'/'sn' direction loops the existing recent_step_set + swap-if-backtrack + stairs_up 'u' valve could not resolve. Two reproducible cases isolated: (a) seed=7 elf F15-plant T119 -- pc in a corridor with N/E=walls, S=monster (avoided when weak), W=floor; the wayfinder targets a feature east, _swap_if_backtrack returns 'e' because 'e' (a wall) isn't in recent_step_set (which tracks tile positions, not wall-bounces), 'e' fails, agent backtracks 'w', repeat. (b) seed=13 human F16 T282 -- pc landed on U at (1,1) with only S walkable; U is explicitly EXCLUDED from visited_features (the line 2479 carve-out -- 'we want the wayfinder to re-target stairs for retreat'), so after stepping S, the BFS retargets U from (1,2), the agent steps N back onto U, oscillation. Two harness changes in playtest_harness.py: (1) Freeze detector: every step() now compares (z, x, y, hp, kills_on_floor) to the prior step; identical = freeze_streak++, else reset to 0. Exposed in obs as `freeze_streak`. Catches pure tile-freezing (the lantern wedge keeps pc.xy static because 'l' doesn't tick a game turn for hunger/spawns). (2) Wedge-break at top of smart_policy: when freeze_streak >= 30 in any movement-capable mode OR oscillation.streak >= 60 in game_loop, override the policy's next action with a random walkable, non-blocked, non-recent cardinal direction. Three-tier fallback: tier 1 picks from non-recent walkable; tier 2 allows recent (escape > anti-backtrack); tier 3 returns 'pass' to advance world state if completely cornered. Mini-sweep verification: 90 runs (30 seeds x 3 races x 1500T F15-plant) -- pre-fix: 9/90 wedged; post-fix: 2/90 fired the wedge break and resolved cleanly, 0/90 unresolved oscillation, 0/90 frozen >50T, 0/90 low-moves stuck. Mean moves 373/run (vs ~0 for wedged pre-fix runs). Thresholds chosen above the existing valves (oscillation 60 > stairs_up 50, freeze 30 > typical mid-mode multi-turn handlers like chest open / pool drink) to avoid false-positives on legitimate multi-turn interactions.",
    "Higher-level playtest wiring: --start-floor N + new_game(start_floor=N) (build 394). The F2-F5 mortality cluster (handoff) drowns the signal on mid/late-floor features in normal sweeps -- 0/18 b390 agents reached F20 to exercise Magic Shoppes; spell-memorize, permanent elixirs, and high-INT crafting all sit downstream of the early death wall. New harness knob plants the character on F<N> with a median-survivor profile so a sweep can iterate on deep-floor mechanics without waiting on 4000T runs to filter survivors. Implementation: new_game accepts `start_floor=N` (default 1 = unchanged). When >1, two helpers run after the normal init: (1) _generate_floors_and_plant_at calls my_tower.add_floor(**gs.floor_params) until F<N> exists, finds the U tile, places pc on it, then flips discovered=True on every tile in F1..F<N-1> so the smart-policy wayfinder can immediately path back to earlier vendors / shrines. (2) _plant_survivor_baseline grants gain_experience((target_level*5)**2 + 1) where target_level = max(1, N-2), spends the resulting (level-1)//2 unspent_stat_points race-flavored (dwarf -> STR/STR/DEX, elf -> INT/INT/DEX, human -> STR/DEX/INT), upgrades equipped weapon/armor by (N-1)//3, pads gold by 150g/floor, and refills HP/MP. session.max_z_via_stairs is pre-banked to pc.z so the retreat policy doesn't fire on turn one. The _trigger_room_interaction call at end of new_game is SKIPPED when planted (standing on U would auto-fire stairs_up_mode). CLI: --start-floor N. Verified: seed=5 F10 human at L8 HP 102 gold 1720 weapon +3 armor +3 engages a Hardened Gnoll L9 on turn 2, flees and heals at turn 5-9. seed=42 F15 elf at L13 HP 148 MP 110 retreats to earlier floors for 1800g of vendor stockpile across 100T.",
    "Off-by-one in b391 tomb_elite cap (build 393). The bug-hunt sweep caught my own mistake: dungeon.py:add_floor:459 passed `len(self.floors)` (0-indexed, BEFORE the append at the end of the method) into `setup_dungeons_and_tombs(new_floor, floor_number)`. Other branches in the same method (bug-level checks at 450/452) use the local `floor_number = len(self.floors) + 1` from line 333. The b391 cap at line 697 `if floor_number >= 5:` therefore over-corrected by one floor: F5 was supposed to be the first floor where elites could spawn, but with the off-by-one the cap also suppressed F5 elites. 20-seed spawn survey on b391: F5 had 40 tombs and 0 elites; F6-F10 had 0.65-0.80 elites/tomb. Fix: pass the 1-indexed `floor_number` variable instead. b393 spawn survey confirms F5+ now spawns elites at the expected rate while F1-F4 remain zero. Also corrected a misleading comment in the same block -- it claimed 'four floor-leveled guardians' per tomb, but `setup_dungeons_and_tombs` only converts adjacent `.` tiles (walls / other M tiles / other rooms are skipped), so the actual mean is 1-4 guardians per tomb depending on adjacency.",
    "Bug hunt: silent AttributeError + report bugs + fey-garden shape (build 392). Five bugs in the same shape as the b385 Potion.use() crash (and surfaced because that fix made me audit the pattern). (1) Shard of Battle / Shard of Eternity passive bonuses (legendary-monster rewards in combat.py:962) wrote `setattr(player_character, 'base_attack', player_character.base_attack + 3)` -- Character stores those as `_base_attack` / `_base_defense`, so reading the public name raised AttributeError, the lambda crashed, and the shard's +3 attack / +5 defense was never applied. Player got the shard in their bag but with no actual stat bump. (2) The Void altar sacrifice reward (room_actions.py:314) wrote to `player_character._max_mana` -- which doesn't exist; max_mana is a computed @property. The +2 max MP boon silently no-op'd; the hunger-fill path was fine. (3) Same _max_mana AttributeError at Solara T3 pray (room_actions.py:353). The +10 max MP part of the capstone never applied. (4) Inline fey-garden loot_table at room_actions.py:2558 had tuple shape `(name, effect_type, magnitude, value, description)` but the Ingredient constructor reads `(description=[1], value=[2], level=[3])` -- so every harvested Moonbell Flower came out with description='mana_boost', value=magnitude (1-3 gold ~free), level=value (15-50 absurdly over-tier). Re-shaped to the canonical `(name, desc, value, level, chance)` matching GARDEN_INGREDIENTS. (5) HTML report inventory truncation at playtest_report.py:1573: `for i in inv[:24]` dropped late-game slots. Crafted sausages routinely land at slot 60+ and vanished from the rendered table. Removed cap. (6) Vendor 'gold spent' column inflated at playtest_report.py:1508: `cur[1] + price * c` -- but the parsed log line 'You bought N x ITEM for P gold' carries P = `new_item.calculated_value` (total stack cost), not per-unit. Bug surfaced on Flare bundles where count=5 multiplied the already-total price by 5. Fix: drop the `* c`.",
    "Hard floor cap on tomb_elite at z>=5 (build 391). Single-line spawn-time fix in dungeon.py:setup_dungeons_and_tombs -- tombs on F1-F4 now still get four floor-leveled undead guardians, but no +1-level 1.3x-stat elite. The b389 death-cause sweep attributed 3/17 deaths (~18%) to ELITE UNDEAD WRAITH / SPECTER at F2-F5: a F3 elite Wraith has 32 atk * 1.3 = 41 raw, kills an L3 player (def~5 HP~50) in 2 rounds. Smart-policy flee gate fires correctly but the parting blow + adjacent re-engage on tight early floors finish under-levelled agents anyway. The b390 T-tile wayfinder avoid and heal-before-flee defended after-the-fact; this cap removes the trap at spawn time. By F5 the player has ~60-80 HP and Stone Skin / +DEF gear in reach, so the elite threshold lines up with the level where the +1-level 1.3x-stat tier is survivable. Cleaner than the b390 wayfinder + flee tweaks because it operates at the property-flagging step in dungeon.py:688 before the monster object exists, so no harness or combat-policy code needs to know about the cap.",
    "Tomb-tile wayfinder avoid + narrow heal-before-flee (build 390). Investigation into deep-floor mortality from the handoff. The b389 sweep revealed monster scaling isn't the killer -- Hardened+ encounters are only 2% of combats with 0 deaths. The real lethal patterns: tomb elite undead at F2-F4 (3/17 baseline deaths to ELITE UNDEAD WRAITH / SPECTER) and brutal parting blows on flee. Two playtest_harness.py interventions: (1) T-tile wayfinder avoid -- under-levelled agents (pc.level < pc.floor + 3, mirrors blocked_guardian_dirs gate) no longer target discovered tomb tiles, so the BFS first_step won't pull them toward elite-guardian corners. Trapped exception drops the avoid when no D is reachable so the agent can still pray for boons. (2) Heal-before-flee in combat_mode -- when monster_too_tough AND HP between 50-65% AND a heal pot is in bag, drink first then flee next turn. Tighter than full HP<80% gate because heals cap at max_hp (>65% wastes the heal) and HP<50% the existing HP-low gate already fires. Both interventions are defensive code grounded in the death-cause analysis; n=18 sweep variance (+/-2 deaths between runs) is too noisy to show statistically clean improvement, but the changes are theoretically sound and don't regress mean floor (human 5.33 / elf 3.50 / dwarf 5.50, comparable to b389).",
]
